& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The retroperitoneum and pelvic extraperitoneum are complex anatomic spaces that contain numerous vital structures such as major vessels, lymphatics, nerves, and abdominopelvic organs. These regions are divided by fascial planes into distinct compartments with defined boundaries and contents, which guide the spread of disease within and beyond the abdominopelvic cavity. The retroperitoneum represents the abdominal part of the extraperitoneum located posterior to the parietal peritoneum and extends from the diaphragm superiorly to the pelvic brim inferiorly. The pelvic extraperitoneum, also referred to as the subperitoneal space, is located below the peritoneal reflection and surrounds the pelvic organs. The extraperitoneal spaces are susceptible to numerous diseases and pathologic processes, reflecting the diversity of structures they contain. These conditions can be congenital, inflammatory, infectious, neoplastic, or traumatic in nature. Imaging modalities such as CT and MRI are indispensable for identifying normal anatomy and characterizing pathologic processes. Patterns of disease spread in these compartments depend on the structures involved and the nature of the disease process. Malignancies often spread via lymphatic and hematogenous routes, while inflammatory and infectious processes tend to track along fascial planes. Vascular pathologic processes, including aneurysms and dissections, can cause secondary effects on adjacent structures. Understanding the anatomic landmarks, imaging features, and patterns of disease spread within the retroperitoneum and pelvic extraperitoneum is critical for accurate diagnosis and effective disease management.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2026</div><div role="paragraph">Supplemental material is available for this article.</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i3" class="graphic" aria-label="Visual abstract containing a key image and key points of the article."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/large/rg.250022.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" aria-labelledby="_i3" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=_i3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.250022">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.250022">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Flowchart of the anatomic classification of the abdominopelvic extraperitoneum and related spaces."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig1.jpg" height="833" width="2250" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Flowchart shows the anatomic classification of the abdominopelvic extraperitoneum and related spaces.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Axial diagram of retroperitoneal anatomy, spaces, boundaries, and relationships."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig2.jpg" height="603" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Axial diagram shows the retroperitoneal anatomy, associated spaces, their boundaries, and anatomic relationships.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Sagittal diagram of pelvic extraperitoneal anatomy and related structures."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig3.jpg" height="924" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Sagittal diagram shows the pelvic extraperitoneal anatomy and related structures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Axial diagram of pelvic extraperitoneum, fasciae, spaces, and anatomic relations."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig4.jpg" height="589" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Axial diagram shows the pelvic extraperitoneum, pelvic fasciae, pelvic extraperitoneal spaces, and their anatomic relationships.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing extensive necrotic retroperitoneal fluid collections from pancreatic necrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig5.jpg" height="628" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Extensive peripancreatic and retroperitoneal necrotic fluid collections in a 58-year-old man with a known history of pancreatic necrosis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows bilateral retroperitoneal necrotic fluid collections, with the left side being more prominent. The left-sided collection partially encircles the left kidney and expands the interfascial planes, specifically the retromesenteric plane (curved black arrow) and the retrorenal plane (straight white arrow). There is also mild extension into the left lateroconal interfascial plane (straight black arrow), along with mild wall thickening of the adjacent descending colon. The fluid continues to track inferiorly along the combined interfascial plane (not shown) and extends into the pelvis. Additionally, a large fluid collection is observed in the lesser sac (curved white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI showing multiple fluid collections expanding retroperitoneal interfascial planes in pancreatitis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig6.jpg" height="668" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Multiple fluid collections, primarily involving the interfascial planes, in a 53-year-old man with a known history of recurrent pancreatitis. Axial T2-weighted MR image shows several fluid collections that expand the retromesenteric plane (white arrows) and the retrorenal plane (arrowheads), accompanied by diffuse edema and fluid signal intensity within the perinephric space (black arrow). These findings are consistent with widespread inflammation and extension of inflammatory fluid along retroperitoneal interfascial planes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Flowchart of diagnostic approach to pneumo-retroperitoneum and pelvic extraperitoneum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig7.jpg" height="759" width="2250" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Flowchart shows a diagnostic approach to pneumoretroperitoneum and pelvic extraperitoneum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Radiograph and CT showing retroperitoneal gas after duodenal perforation post-ERCP."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig8.jpg" height="835" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Extraluminal retroperitoneal gas from duodenal perforation in a 55-year-old man after endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography with biliary stent placement. <b>(A)</b> Frontal abdominal radiograph shows streaky lucencies in the right abdomen (white arrows) and outlining the right kidney (black arrow), indicative of retroperitoneal gas. Note the biliary stent in place (arrowhead). <b>(B)</b> Axial CT image (lung window) confirms the presence of gas in the right retroperitoneum (arrow). The air extends across the midline through the interfascial planes (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing pneumoretroperitoneum from descending colon perforation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig9.jpg" height="771" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Pneumoretroperitoneum in a 49-year-old man with descending colon perforation following polypectomy. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows extraluminal gas within the left perinephric space (arrows), with extension into the lateroconal fascial plane and posterior pararenal space, reaching the preperitoneal space (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing infected pancreatic necrosis extending into the liver."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig10.jpg" height="743" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Air collection in a 66-year-old man with infected pancreatic necrosis and extension of the necrotic fluid into the liver parenchyma/perihepatic region. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous pancreatic or peripancreatic collection in the APS. The collection contains air foci (white arrows). The collection extends from the APS into the hepatic parenchyma and/or the subcapsular region of the liver (black arrow). The communication between the two collections is marked by the white arrowhead. Additionally, pneumobilia is present, likely due to a prior sphincterotomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing infected walled-off pancreatic necrosis extending to pelvis and transverse mesocolon."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig11.jpg" height="1146" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Necrotizing pancreatitis and infected walled-off necrosis extending into the pelvis and transverse mesocolon in a 61-year-old man. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows an infected pancreatic walled-off necrosis with internal gas foci (*). The necrotic material and gas foci spread within the APS (straight white arrow), extending inferiorly into the pelvic extraperitoneum (black arrow) and anteriorly to the transverse mesocolon (curved white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm with large retroperitoneal hematoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig12.jpg" height="791" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm in a 76-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a fusiform abdominal aortic aneurysm (straight white arrow) with associated large retroperitoneal hematoma (arrowhead), consistent with features of abdominal aortic aneurysm rupture and leakage. The hematoma outlines the surrounding interfascial planes and extends inferiorly into the pelvis (black arrow) along the combined interfascial plane (curved white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing large right retroperitoneal hematoma extending into pelvic spaces."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig13.jpg" height="998" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Large right retroperitoneal hematoma in a 71-year-old man. Sagittal noncontrast CT image shows a large right retroperitoneal hematoma primarily occupying the right posterior pararenal space (black arrowheads) and extends along the retromesenteric plane (white arrowhead). The hematoma tracks along the combined interfascial plane and the posterior pararenal space into the pelvic extraperitoneal spaces (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing traumatic left renal rupture with active bleeding and perinephric hematoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig14.jpg" height="758" width="1699" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Traumatic left renal injury and active bleeding following a motor vehicle accident in a 56-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images in both arterial <b>(A)</b> and venous <b>(B)</b> phases show a ruptured left kidney with active arterial bleeding (arrowheads in <b>A</b>) and a large hematoma in the perinephric space (arrows in <b>A</b>). The extravasated contrast material increases in size and extent on the venous phase image <b>(B)</b> (arrowheads in <b>B</b>), confirming persistent active bleeding. Notably, the attenuation of areas of active bleeding corresponds to the blood pool.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing retroperitoneal hemorrhage from metastatic melanoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig15.jpg" height="649" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Metastatic hemorrhagic melanoma and retroperitoneal hematoma in a 68-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows extensive retroperitoneal hemorrhage in the perirenal space (white arrow) with midline extension along the retromesenteric plane (black arrows). A subcutaneous metastatic nodule in the right flank is noted (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing retroperitoneal urinoma from left kidney injury."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig16.jpg" height="637" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Retroperitoneal urine leak in a 56-year-old man with left kidney injury. Axial delayed urographic phase contrast-enhanced CT image shows contrast material leakage from the left collecting system (black arrow) into the left perinephric space, indicating a retroperitoneal urine leak or urinoma. A perinephric collection (curved white arrow) is noted, with fluid extending along the retrorenal plane (arrowhead) and the retromesenteric plane, crossing the midline (straight white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="CT cystography showing extraperitoneal bladder rupture with “molar tooth” appearance."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig17.jpg" height="693" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Extraperitoneal bladder rupture in a 45-year-old woman involved in a motor vehicle collision. Axial CT cystographic image shows urine contrast material leak into the prevesical space (arrows), forming the distinctive “molar tooth” appearance, a classic sign of extraperitoneal bladder rupture. There was an associated fracture of the left pubic bone (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing perinephric abscess confined to the perinephric space."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig18.jpg" height="646" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a complex perinephric fluid collection with peripheral rim enhancement (*), consistent with an abscess, in a 47-year-old man with a perinephric abscess. The collection is confined within the perinephric space, with no extension into adjacent compartments. The APS (arrowheads) and the posterior pararenal space (arrows) remain intact, indicating localized infection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing displacement patterns differentiating intraperitoneal and retroperitoneal masses."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig19.jpg" height="773" width="1850" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Differentiating intraperitoneal from retroperitoneal masses. <b>(A)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a large peritoneal mass with mass effect on retroperitoneal structures, causing posterior displacement of the ascending and descending colon (arrows). This displacement pattern is a typical feature for intraperitoneal masses that helps differentiate them from retroperitoneal masses. <b>(B)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen in a different patient shows a retroperitoneal low-attenuation mass resulting in anterior displacement of the right-sided colon and displacement of the duodenum and small bowel loops to the contralateral left side (arrows). This displacement pattern coincides with the retroperitoneal location of the mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI showing renal angiomyolipoma mimicking retroperitoneal liposarcoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig20.jpg" height="1243" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Left renal angiomyolipoma mimicking a retroperitoneal liposarcoma in a 43-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced MR image shows a heterogeneously enhancing soft-tissue mass (arrows) with predominantly fat signal intensity arising from the inferior pole of the left kidney. A feeding vessel arising from the kidney (arrowhead) is noted, confirming its renal origin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic" aria-label="Flowchart of extraperitoneal mass classification by imaging features."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig21.jpg" height="884" width="2250" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Flowchart shows the classification of extraperitoneal masses according to their imaging features. <i>IgG4</i> = immunoglobulin G4, <i>RD</i> = related disease, <i>RP</i> = retroperitoneal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing renal cell carcinoma with transfascial spread."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig22.jpg" height="799" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. RCC with transfascial spread in a 61-year-old man. Axial postcontrast CT image of the abdomen shows a heterogeneous mass in the superior pole of the left kidney that invades the anterior renal fascia (white arrow) and extends anterolaterally along the splenorenal ligament (curved black arrow). The mass also invades the posterior renal fascia (straight black arrow), with extension into the posterior pararenal space and along the lateroconal fascial plane (arrowheads). Note the associated intraperitoneal extension with scalloping of the lateral splenic surface.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI showing rectal cancer invading the mesorectal fascia."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig23.jpg" height="831" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Rectal cancer with mesorectal fascia invasion in a 60-year-old man. Coronal oblique T2-weighted MR image shows an irregular circumferential rectal wall mass (black arrow) with mixed signal intensity. The mass has an exophytic component (white arrow) invading the mesorectal fascia (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI showing urothelial carcinoma invading retroperitoneal spaces and vessels."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig24.jpg" height="831" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span>. Urothelial carcinoma of the upper urinary tract invading the adjacent retroperitoneal spaces in a 69-year-old man. Coronal T1-weighted contrast-enhanced fat-saturated MR image shows an infiltrative inhomogeneous enhancing soft-tissue mass involving the right renal pelvis and renal hilum (black arrows) with extension into the right perinephric space (not shown). The mass extends medially to the vascular space with encasement of the IVC and abutment of the right aspect of the abdominal aorta (arrowheads). Superiorly, the mass extends into the upper retroperitoneum and infiltrates the right periureteral tissues and right psoas muscle inferiorly (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing metastatic retroperitoneal disease from prostate cancer."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig25.jpg" height="967" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span>. Metastatic retroperitoneal disease in a 68-year-old man with a known history of prostate cancer. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows large heterogeneous retroperitoneal masses (arrows) involving both kidneys and ureters, more prominent on the right side. The masses extend into the perinephric spaces with periureteric spread down to the pelvis, resulting in bilateral collecting system dilatation (arrowheads). The lesion was biopsied and proved to be retroperitoneal metastatic disease from prostate cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing recurrent endometrial cancer invading the left perinephric space."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig26.jpg" height="950" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Recurrent serous endometrial cancer in a 57-year-old woman. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows disease recurrence in the form of an infiltrative soft-tissue mass encasing the left ureter, ureteric stent, and left renal hilum with a soft-tissue component in the perinephric space (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing extraosseous myeloma presenting as large retroperitoneal mass."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig27.jpg" height="948" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Extraosseous myelomatous mass in the extraperitoneum in a 74-year-old man with a known history of multiple myeloma. Coronal <b>(A)</b> and sagittal <b>(B)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a large infiltrative soft-tissue mass (arrows) centered in the left retroperitoneum without a clear connection to the osseous structures. The mass extends medially to the vascular space, with encasement of the infrarenal abdominal aorta and IVC. Superiorly, the mass is inseparable from the mid left ureter with upstream mild hydroureter, likely related to ureteric compression or invasion (white arrowheads). Inferiorly, the mass encases the left iliac vessels (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28" class="graphic" aria-label="CT and ultrasound showing retroperitoneal metastasis from testicular cancer."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig28.jpg" height="582" width="1499" aria-labelledby="fig28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28</span>. Metastatic retroperitoneal lymph nodes from testicular cancer in a 29-year-old man. <b>(A)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large heterogeneous retroperitoneal mass (arrows) with encasement and displacement of the abdominal aorta and renal vessels. The mass extends to the left renal hilum and partially surrounds the left kidney. <b>(B)</b> Color Doppler US image of the left testicle shows a hypoechoic mass (arrow) with internal vascularity, confirming the primary testicular malignancy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI showing renal cell carcinoma with malignant thrombus extending into IVC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig29.jpg" height="651" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig29" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span>. Malignant thrombosis involving the right renal vein and IVC secondary to RCC in a 71-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a large heterogeneously enhancing mass in the right kidney (arrowhead), pathologically confirmed as clear cell RCC. The right renal vein is distended by a soft-tissue mass (white arrows) exhibiting signal intensity characteristics similar to those of the primary tumor, consistent with a malignant thrombus. The thrombus further extends into the adjacent segment of the IVC (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig29">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI showing rectal cancer with extramural vascular invasion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig30.jpg" height="2026" width="998" aria-labelledby="fig30" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30</span>. Rectal cancer with extramural vascular invasion (EMVI) in a 65-year-old man. Coronal T2-weighted <b>(A)</b> and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(B)</b> MR images show circumferential mural thickening of the rectum (arrowhead). Irregular, serpiginous, linear, and nodular areas of tumor signal intensity are observed extending along the right lateral aspect of the rectum, consistent with tumor infiltration into the perirectal vessels, indicative of extramural venous invasion (EMVI) (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig30">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing leiomyosarcoma of the inferior vena cava."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig31.jpg" height="833" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig31" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31</span>. Leiomyosarcoma of the IVC in a 72-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large heterogeneous enhancing soft-tissue mass with an exophytic component (arrows) arising from the medial wall of the IVC. The mass extends into the aortocaval space and shows central low-attenuation areas suggestive of necrosis. The mass causes mass effect on the IVC and partial narrowing of its lumen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig31">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing leiomyosarcoma of the left colic vein."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig32.jpg" height="1102" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig32" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32</span>. Leiomyosarcoma of the left colic vein in a 58-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images show a small heterogeneously enhancing soft-tissue mass (arrow in <b>A</b>) inseparable from the left colic vein (arrow in <b>B</b>), pathologically proven to be a retroperitoneal leiomyosarcoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig32">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig33" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI showing recurrent pelvic sidewall tumor with perineural and periureteric invasion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig33.jpg" height="666" width="1898" aria-labelledby="fig33" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33</span>. Left pelvic side wall tumor recurrence and perineural and periureteric invasion in a 44-year-old woman with a history of rectal cancer. Coronal <b>(A)</b> and axial <b>(B)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a left pelvic sidewall biopsy-proved recurrent mass lesion (straight white arrow in <b>A</b>). The mass encases the left ureter (curved white arrow in <b>A</b>) and extends to the left greater sciatic foramen with involvement of the sciatic nerve and left internal iliac vessels. The left sciatic nerve shows diffuse nodular thickening (black arrowhead in <b>A</b>). There is abnormal signal intensity within the left iliopsoas muscle (white arrowheads in <b>B</b>) compared with the normal contralateral right side, denoting muscle denervation. The linear filling defect within the left ureter represents a partially visualized ureteric stent.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig33">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig34" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing retroperitoneal lymphoma encasing major vessels."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig34.jpg" height="711" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig34" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34</span>. Retroperitoneal lymphoma in a 31-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a large homogeneous retroperitoneal mass (arrows) with encasement and anterior displacement of the abdominal aorta (arrowhead) and renal vessels rather than effacing them. The masses occupy the midline vascular space and extend bilaterally into the perinephric spaces.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig34">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig35" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing IgG4-related retroperitoneal fibrosis causing ureteral obstruction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig35.jpg" height="1048" width="1698" aria-labelledby="fig35" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 35</span>. IgG4-related retroperitoneal fibrosis in a 55-year-old man. Coronal <b>(A)</b> and axial <b>(B)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show left perinephric and bilateral periureteral soft-tissue masses (arrows) causing marked left and mild right collecting system dilatation, with cortical atrophy of the left kidney (white arrowhead in <b>A</b>). The ureters are medially deviated, and ureteral stents are noted (black arrowheads). The soft-tissue masses extend along the abdominal aorta down to the aortic bifurcation while sparing the posterior aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig35">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig36" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing Erdheim-Chester disease with perinephric soft tissue and “coated aorta” sign."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig36.jpg" height="612" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig36" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 36</span>. Perinephric soft-tissue masses in Erdheim-Chester disease in a 46-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows bilateral perinephric soft-tissue infiltration (white arrows) with an atrophic right kidney (black arrow) and periaortic involvement (arrowheads), consistent with the “coated aorta” sign, a classic feature of Erdheim-Chester disease. Unlike retroperitoneal fibrosis, Erdheim-Chester disease typically spares the IVC and distal ureters.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig36">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig37" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing pancreatic adenocarcinoma invading spleen with liver metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig37.jpg" height="790" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig37" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 37</span>. Locally advanced adenocarcinoma of the tail of the pancreas in a 53-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows an ill-defined hypoenhancing mass in the tail of the pancreas (arrow) seen extending along the splenorenal ligament and invading the spleen. Multiple liver metastases are also noted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig37">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig38" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing inflammatory fluid from pancreatitis extending to abdominal wall."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig38.jpg" height="576" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig38" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 38</span>. Abdominal wall extension of the associated inflammatory or infected fluid collection in a 60-year-old woman with a known history of complicated pancreatitis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a relatively high-attenuation fluid collection with peripheral enhancement within the APS. The collection reaches the lateroconal plane and the preperitoneal space with extension through the left lateral anterior abdominal wall (arrow). These findings are likely related to the effect of pancreatic enzymes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig38">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig39" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy with transdiaphragmatic extension in germ cell tumor."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig39.jpg" height="1238" width="1498" aria-labelledby="fig39" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 39</span>. Metastatic retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy with transdiaphragmatic extension in a 23-year-old man with a history of nonseminomatous mixed germ cell tumor. Coronal <b>(A)</b> and sagittal <b>(B)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show metastatic retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy (white arrowheads) extending superiorly through the retrocrural space (straight white arrow). There is further transdiaphragmatic extension (black arrowheads in <b>A</b>) with associated left pleural metastatic masses (curved white arrow in <b>A</b>), consistent with pleural dissemination.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig39">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig40" class="graphic" aria-label="CT showing retroperitoneal liposarcoma extending into inguinal canal and thigh."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250022/asset/images/rg.250022.fig40.jpg" height="1085" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig40" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 40</span>. Retroperitoneal liposarcoma extending into the inguinal canal and upper thigh in a 72-year-old woman. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large right inferior retroperitoneal (arrowheads) and pelvic extraperitoneal fat-containing mass with high-attenuation solid components within, consistent with a liposarcoma. The mass extends inferiorly through the right inguinal canal (arrow) into the upper thigh (black arrowheads)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250022&amp;id=fig40">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Mirilas P, Skandalakis JE. Surgical Anatomy of the Retroperitoneal Spaces Part II: The Architecture of the Retroperitoneal Space. <em>Am Surg</em> 2010;76(1):33–42.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1177/000313481007600108">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20135937/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Surgical+Anatomy+of+the+Retroperitoneal+Spaces+Part+II%3A+The+Architecture+of+the+Retroperitoneal+Space&amp;author=P+Mirilas&amp;author=JE+Skandalakis&amp;publication_year=2010&amp;journal=Am+Surg&amp;pages=33-42&amp;doi=10.1177%2F000313481007600108&amp;pmid=20135937">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Gaballah AH, Shaaban AM, Elguindy YM, Elsayes KM. The Extraperitoneal Spaces. In: <em>Cross-Sectional Imaging of the Abdomen and Pelvis [Internet]</em>. New York, NY: Springer New York 2015: 483–567.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4939-1884-3_17">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+Extraperitoneal+Spaces&amp;author=AH+Gaballah&amp;author=AM+Shaaban&amp;author=YM+Elguindy&amp;author=KM+Elsayes&amp;publication_year=2015&amp;pages=483-567&amp;doi=10.1007%2F978-1-4939-1884-3_17">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Gaballah AH, Algazzar M, Kazi IA, et al. The Peritoneum: Anatomy, Pathologic Findings, and Patterns of Disease Spread. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 2024;44(8):e230216.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.230216">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39088361/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+Peritoneum%3A+Anatomy%2C+Pathologic+Findings%2C+and+Patterns+of+Disease+Spread&amp